##China has slowed the global spread of the virus, and the public health race is only just beginning

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

The new crown epidemic is a global disaster and a training ground for public health in many countries.

According to WHO expert and Professor David Hyman, an epidemiologist at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, the more important factor preventing the spread of the new coronavirus is the strength of a country's health care system, is its ability to immediately monitor and treat patients who may have symptoms.

So what is the strength of a country's public health? Tom Frieden, a former director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and now president and CEO of the Resolve to Save Lives nonprofit organization, said: Early Warning Systems to screen for early outbreaks, networks of laboratory information exchanges, disease detection facilities, rapid response teams, and communication, legal, logistics and planning capabilities are all necessary to prevent outbreaks from spiraling out of control.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | national distribution of confirmed cases of COVID-19 on March 1. (Source: China Center for Disease Control)

Take early warning, for example, "In this outbreak, China has actually missed the window of early warning, resulting in thousands of times the cost and resources we need to launch national epidemic prevention and control, " said Zhang Wenhong, director of the infection department at the Fudan University Hospital in Mount Hua, the article was published on February 28 on the public account Mount Hua infection.

Thanks to the subsequent "epidemic" in the war, China has made the new coronavirus research data and epidemic information open and transparent, in order to control the spread of the epidemic to take strict preventive measures, in the doubt won the first stage of victory. Bruce Aylward, a senior adviser to the WHO Director General, said: "We need to recognize the contribution of the people of Wuhan and the world owes you. When this epidemic is over, I hope to have the opportunity to thank the people of Wuhan once again on behalf of the world. I know that the Chinese people have contributed a lot during this epidemic."

Ning Yi, a professor at Peking University's Public Health, told DeepTech that China's move was a "remarkable contribution" in slowing the spread of the virus and giving other countries time to prepare for an outbreak.

Today, Italy, South Korea and Iran are all emerging points of the new crown. "If other countries don't catch up, then the infected people from other countries may flow back to China, " Ning warned. Apparently, this is a new problem at this stage.

Others think Singapore has done a good job in the outbreak, but the rocks are for reference only, not for rough copying. Who director-general Dr. Tan Desai said that there is no one-size-fits-all approach to new crown outbreaks and that each country must conduct its own risk assessment for its own situation.

In Ning Yi's view, a country's public health strength is not just a pile of numbers, but a strategic choice based on the specific circumstances of the time and place. Relative to those public health hard indicators, he attaches more importance to the national health quality and disaster prevention quality. He gave us a new perspective.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | global distribution of confirmed cases of COVID-19 PNEUMONIA | March 1. (Source: China Center for Disease Control)

DEEPTECH: The director-general of the World Health Organization (who) has said that it is not yet possible to determine whether the new outbreak is a global pandemic. How do you evaluate the development of the current outbreak?

Ning Yi: At least now China has made a contribution to the containment of the epidemic. Whether or not it kills the disease, I think the data reported so far, should be able to contain it during the epidemic season, China has greatly slowed the spread of the virus. At present, many provinces have not been diagnosed for many days in a row, and the situation in these provinces has become more optimistic.

If the rest of the world doesn't catch up, the rest of the world's infections could flow back to China. China's approach has contributed significantly to slowing the spread of the virus, giving other countries time to prepare for an outbreak. For a new virus, slowing down the epidemic and better understanding its properties is in itself a way of buying time to prepare for a response, They Knew What They Wanted up the case fatality rate and, at the same time, systematically contain losses.

The contrast between Wuhan and other provinces is striking. In the early period, the medical resources in Wuhan were crowded, which indirectly led to the shortage of medical resources, and the mortality rate was very high. Once the rate of spread has been brought under control, other provinces will be in a position to control case fatality and cope with other losses.

In our early response to the outbreak, it would have been better if the information had been transparent or handled in a timely manner. But generally speaking, when the new disease occurs, people often need a period of time to judge and understand the characteristics of this pathogen and epidemic development, determine the main means of prevention and control.

There are some issues that can be reviewed, but subsequent measures can help contain or delay its spread at home and even internationally.

DEEPTECH: The new outbreak is an opportunity to show the public health strength of countries. How do you think the public health strength of countries is reflected in this outbreak?

Ning Yi: here are a few factors. First of all, the assessment of the epidemic in different countries is not the same, the evaluation of control effect is not limited to public health. What controls are in place? Can these measures be guaranteed? There are many options. It is also necessary to consider how long the measures will take to achieve what effect, how the impact on public health, as well as economic, social development, cultural, diplomatic and other aspects of the impact.

Secondly, people's consciousness and education of disaster prevention in peacetime. For example, Japan is a disaster-prone country, relatively speaking, its people to the earthquake, tsunami and other disasters more mature mentality, usually also have exercises and training, disaster comes, everyone knows their position and responsibility. This outbreak, a large number of patients in Wuhan rushed to the hospital for treatment, medical resources crowding effect is obvious. Japan may also be expected to have a run, but a strong sense of disaster prevention, there will not be such a serious medical resources run, and then a lot of chain reaction. It is also important that prevention outside the hospital is better when it is prepared.

In addition, this is usually with the national health education or health related quality. A better understanding of the basics of disease prevention, combined with intensified education in emergency response, may make it easier to respond to outbreaks. In the case of Wuhan, if we want to achieve the same educational effect, it may take a considerable period of time to educate the people, which is also the cost of time and resources, and time does not wait for people in the control of the epidemic.

In addition, it is critical to make a comprehensive assessment of the capacity of the country's disease control system and how to be more proactive in the prevention and control of the epidemic, including preparedness plans and resources to deal with the epidemic. This is a test of soft power, soft power is not built up in a short period of time.

Of course, the virus is temperature dependent, and high temperatures may also reduce the transmission and virulence of the new coronavirus. This is not confirmed and more information is needed on the development of the disease in Singapore.

Nationally, we have a better understanding of the new coronavirus after a period of time since the new crown disease, and the ability to quickly stamp out some small epidemics has been developed in various places.

DEEPTECH: The public health strength of a country or region is a very comprehensive thing, and it is not a quantitative indicator. Is Wuhan a special case under the present circumstances?

Ning Yi: the strength of a country's public health is comprehensive. First of all, civic education is important. Regardless of whether Japan and Singapore are right or wrong, at least they have drills and training to deal with disasters, and they still have some confidence in their citizens'knowledge of disaster prevention. Especially because of Japan's frequent disasters, such as tsunamis and earthquakes, it does not mean that the country's leaders must come forward at this time, but rather that ordinary people immediately know what they need to do to protect themselves and obey the overall situation.

In addition, the quality of citizens'basic education is important. If the basic education is good, they will soon understand what you ask them to do. This is a long-term educational problem. At the same time, I think the long-term construction of public health system includes public health education from people to all levels of health practitioners.

Third, it may also depend on the economic impact of the outbreak. Singapore, for example, could be fatal to its economic development if it did something particularly drastic. The cost of response measures and its profit and loss, need to do a comprehensive evaluation.

Public Health strength is more or a soft power, so this is a combination of factors.

For Wuhan, the case fatality rate was very high at the beginning. Among the first 99 patients at Wuhan Jinyintan hospital reported by the Lancet, the death rate as of January 25 was at least 10 percent. The high case fatality rate in the early stages led China to take some very strict measures, which were the basis of its decision making. At present, the case fatality rate in Hubei Province has been greatly reduced. Let's look outside Hubei Province. The crude case fatality rate is close to 0.6% , which is close to the case fatality rate of influenza.

DEEPTECH: Singapore has a strong public health system. Some scholars have praised Singapore's transparency this time. What do you think?

Ning Yi: Singapore's information is indeed transparent and open, which is very helpful to its epidemic control. We also have successful experiences in China. For example, the plague in Beijing a while ago is a good example. It is more open and transparent, people are more alert, and people know how to take the initiative to prevent it, there wasn't much panic in the process.

At this stage of the epidemic is still open and transparent, such as the February 20 release of the Peking University People's Hospital epidemic. But there are still big problems with the public interpretation of the data, making people feel out of step with reality and requiring more detailed interpretation by professionals. For example, the crude death rate of 2%-3% , may not be the same as the doctor's feeling, they seem to feel higher. Because a simple presentation of a number does not take into account the fact that many critically ill patients have not yet finished their treatment cycle, many patients have just been admitted to the hospital, more crudely presented as the denominator, need to have some correct interpretation. This is what I call the soft power of public health.

A brief introduction to Ning Yi

Ning Yi, professor, public health, Peking University, Executive Director, Peking University Health Science Center Institute of Public Health, and director, Minian Institute of Health Industry, Zhongguancun. He holds Bachelor's, master's and doctor's degrees from Peking University, Washington University and Harvard University.

He has been an assistant professor at Peking University, a civil servant at the Ministry of Health, an assistant research fellow at the University of Washington, a research fellow at Harvard Medical School, an assistant professor in the Faculty of Medicine at Virginia Commonwealth University, and a professor and postdoctoral adviser, senior Fellow, GSK Global Senior Fellow, postdoctoral advisor, GSK Tsinghua Center for Global Health, Executive Director, Mercure Institute, Zhongguancun, China.
